  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Federal contract obligations in Utah totaled $4.5B in FY2026 to date, with 6,404 awards and an average award size of $700K. Obligations fell 14.1% year over year. Obligations peaked at $7.2B in FY24 and have declined to $5.2B in FY25 and $4.5B in FY26. The Department of Defense accounts for the largest share of buying agency obligations at $3.6B, followed by the Department of the Treasury at $350M and the Department of Veterans Affairs at $115M. Industry concentration is high: Guided Missile and Space Vehicle Manufacturing accounts for $2.5B of obligations, and Nonferrous Metal Rolling, Drawing, and Extruding accounts for $322M. Vendor concentration is also pronounced, with NORTHROP GRUMMAN SYSTEMS CORP receiving $2.5B and ASAHI REFINING USA INC receiving $322M. The mix of large prime awards and concentrated industry dollars shapes opportunities for defense suppliers, specialty manufacturers, and engineering and R&D firms seeking federal work in Utah.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How has federal contracting in Utah changed over recent years?",
        "body": "Obligations rose from $4B in FY21 to a peak of $7.2B in FY24, then declined to $5.2B in FY25 and to $4.5B in FY26. Overall activity through FY26 shows fewer dollars and a year-over-year decline, with obligations down 14.1% compared with the prior year. Award volume stands at 6,404 awards in FY2026 to date, with an average award size of $700K."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Which sectors and vendors dominate federal spending in Utah?",
        "body": "The Department of Defense dominates agency spending at $3.6B, while the top industry by obligations is Guided Missile and Space Vehicle Manufacturing at $2.5B. NORTHROP GRUMMAN SYSTEMS CORP is the top vendor at $2.5B, followed by ASAHI REFINING USA INC at $322M and L3 TECHNOLOGIES, INC. at $215M. Engineering, R&D, and specialty manufacturing industries also account for substantial shares of obligations."
      }
    ]
  },
